Name: Name 4309
Notes: 17/08/16: met with Esa and others in Helsinki. They definitely face a challenge in mapping instruments. They already use FIGI in SimCorp. They would like to use in more applications, for example, internally built prediction/analytics models but for that they would need validity periods of FIGIs (date created, date made inactive), and also ideally mapped to validity periods for ISINs (for quantitative strategy it is important to know how ISIN evolved over time). That is the reason why other IDs are still being used - they have a code history. They also use Calypso for custodian functionality for IRS, FX, gas derivatives. Overall the IRS is the biggest book in the bank. Other applications used: Orc for equities, Albasec for back office, Dimension for asset management. The regulations applicable to the bank: Basel, MiFID II, solvency II.

Name: Name 4540
Notes:
"""17 Aug 2016: had a meeting with Esa Junttila and a large team representing the trading dept, back office and derivatives. They all work closely together, that's why all were in the meeting to learn more about FIGI. They mentioned that one of the issues they are facing is properly identifying instruments and tying them together (aggregate them). They also have issues with properly identifying shares trading on different exchanges, as currently they rely on ISIN and end up with duplicates. So they were quite interested in FIGI and learning how it can help them solve these challenges. They have equities, bonds and OTC derivatives in their databases. FIGI can be obviously useful for equities and bonds, but also for derivatives - to identify the underlying. Also they noted that ISIN has worked for fixed income so far, but not for convertibles. There is a need for a unique ID globally. FIGI's granularity for equities would help them with getting pricing for stocks on different exchanges. They use SimCorp and utilize the ID_BB_UNIQUE to obtain pricing (which doesn't work if the stock trades on more than one exchange - gets composite pricing).
17 Aug 2016: sent a follow up email with API formula and the levels of FIGI. 
15/09/16: question about NDA SS Equity and NDA1V FH Equity - no common FIGIs. It's because NDA1V FH is a foreign depository receipt and represents only a fraction of the NDA share. """

Name: Name 4544
Notes: Market Data. 10/08/16: met with Stephanie Wolke and Philip Maymann (both senior market data managers). They are well aware of FIGI and like the idea of a single, free identifier for all asset classes as currently they do have to do the cross-mapping exercises. However, many of their internal systems are hard-coded to use Ric codes. They did look into using Magtia services to map from Ric codes, but it would be too expensive for them and hard to justify the business case. Also some of those applications are business critical which makes it harder to make a switch while minimizing any risks to the business. However, if this identifier was a single global ID that everybody would use (eg mandated by regulators or supported by ISO), it would of course make a strong business case for investment. They also use 3rd party vendor apps, for example from Ullink. I told them that many of those apps use FIGI. Also discussed other data vendors that included FIGI in their datasets. They do use them a bit for some asset classes but really  would like to see major vendor like Thompson Reuters carry it as Factset, etc are perceived to be less important, while TR offers breadth and quality of data coverage and therefore they use TR a lot more. Also their customer (counterparty) requests for IDs drive the need to hold many different identifiers in GoldenSource (used by their back office).
